I often think that the millennial generation may be the last one capable of purely appreciating art and forming connections with artists. They don't have that pressure to view everything through a critical, biased lens.
We grew up in the golden age of media, when people shared a common understanding of pop culture, but now that collective consciousness has disappeared.
At that time, we could immerse ourselves directly without worrying about the source of the content, because tracing back origins was not easy back then.
We worshipped these artists, and there was no reason to question that worship. Thus, we formed a "pseudo-social relationship" with them, and regarded it as an essential part of our lives.
This also explains why we are so obsessed with nostalgia.
When the show "The Office" was still airing, my friends and I would gather every Thursday to watch it together, eating pizza and catching up on the episodes.
This is completely different from our current experience of watching shows through streaming platforms. Streaming services usually release all 12 episodes at once, and everyone watches at their own pace. When discussing the plot on social media, people add "spoiler warning" tags, or simply limit the conversation to specific groups.
Subconsciously, we all long for that sense of collective belonging that connected everyone back then.
It's precisely because of this nostalgia that we keep rewatching TV shows like "The Office" or movies like "The King of Comedy," whose iconic lines become memes that spread widely online.
We quote these classic lines from the works and assume that most people will understand them.
Now, even if something goes viral online, we can't assume that everyone has seen it.
With information overload, there's just too much to pay attention to, and it's impossible to filter it down… Do we still have a chance to escape this state of information overload?
We keep discovering new media and new artists, only to find that they are either sexual predators with a history of abuse or stubborn individuals filled with prejudice, and this cycle is exhausting.
We are torn between indulging in nostalgia and having to acknowledge that the people who created the art we love may have serious moral flaws, and this conflicting mindset leaves us feeling lost.
We will be more cautious in forming "pseudo-social relationships" with artists.
We gradually realized that a person who wants to gain wealth and power finds it difficult to ensure they will not harm or exploit others.
Since the collective consciousness of the media no longer exists, we have developed a class consciousness that helps us maintain critical thinking.
Of course, some people are still stubborn and insist on idolizing others, only to pretend to be shocked when the idol falls.
We are in an era of transformation, and I am desperately curious about where we are heading.
